mbroke, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembroke, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Meline","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Ameline</i>, feminine form of <i>Amelin</i> (see   Melin   4)."],"variants":[{"name":"Melin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Alvar, Anders, Hilmer, Hiltrud, Sven.","Swedish: probably an ornamental or habitational name formed with the (placename) element <i>mel</i>, from Old Norse <i>methal</i> ‘mid, middle’, + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’.","Czech (<b>Melín</b>): from a pet form of the personal name   Melichar   ‘Melchior’."]}]},{"name":"Elinor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elinor Meline was born in 1226, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, her father, John Meline, was 16 and her mother, Jane Hubbeston, was 16. She married William Picton in 1249, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1280, in Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1226–Abt 1280":"1226–umbes 1280","1226–1280":"1226–1280","1220–